## Martin Brandenburg: Tensor categorical foundations of algebraic geometry

$2.2 Algebraic geometry

Lemma 2.2.3 (Pullbacks of closed subschemes)
Lemma 2.2.4 (Universal property of immersions).
Let i: Y → X be an immersion of schemes. Then a morphism f: Z→X factors (uniquely) through i if and only if f^∗:Qcoh(X)→Qcoh(Z) maps every homomorphism, which is an isomorphism on Y, to an isomorphism.
Lemma 2.2.5: If f∗ = g∗: Qcoh(Y) → Qcoh(X). Then the underlying maps of f and g coincide. If Y is quasi-separated, we even have f=g.
Corollary 2.2.6: if X,Y qs, f* une équivalence de catégorie, alors f est un
iso.

$2.3 Local presentation

Proposition 2.3.1 (Quasi-coherent modules of finite presentation).
Let X be a qc qs scheme and M be a quasi-coherent module on X. If M is of finite presentation in the usual sense of algebraic geometry, then M is a finitely presentable object. The converse also holds.

Remark 2.3.2. If X is any scheme, then Qcoh(X) is locally λ-presentable for some suitable large regular cardinal λ.

Proposition 2.3.3.
Let X be  a  geometric  stack [=quasi-compact and the diagonal morphism is representable and affine; affine diagonal=semi-separated=l'intersection d'ouverts affines est affine. => there is a smooth (or just flat) surjective affine morphism π: P→X such that P is an affine scheme. Comme Q=Px_X P est affine, X est un smooth commutative groupoide dans la catégorie des schémas affines; cf http://www.math.harvard.edu/~lurie/papers/Tannaka.pdf Remark 3.3]
Si X de plus Deligne-Mumford, ou strong resolution property [= locally
free O X -modules constitute a generator] ou noeth ou
scheme, alors Qcoh(X) est loc. de présentation finie, et un module est de
présentation finie si il l'est au sens standard.

$ Section 2.4: density and local stacks

Lemma 2.4.1: conditions for when the R-linear Kan extension is equal to the
standard Kan extension: les morphismes de base C' sont filtrants, si A,B -> M \in C, alors il existe D dans C' tel que A,B->D->M. Par exemple si C' est stable par somme directe.

Corollary 2.4.3:
If X is a scheme (or more generally an algebraic stack), which has the strong resolution property, then locally free OX-modules constitute a dense subcategory of Qcoh(X).
Prop 2.4.4: si X a la strong resolution property, et M plat, alors si
Spec(M) est affine, M est limite filtrante de modules localement libres
[sur un schéma affine, c'est le théorème de Lazard-Govorov qui dit que M
plat est limite filtrante de modules libres].

$ 2.5: extension

Proposition 2.5.1:
Let C be an abelian R-linear category and D any finitely cocomplete R-linear category. Let C′ be a full replete subcategory of C with the following properties: C' contient 0, tout objet de C vient d'un épi de C', + la condition du Lemme 2.4.1. Let F: C′ → D be an R-linear right exact functor; then F extends to a right R-linear right exact functor Fbar: C → D.

Pr: Fbar est l'extension de Kan R-linéaire de F; que l'on peut calculer
comme suit: on prend une présentation A'->A->M de M par des objets de C',
et on pose Fbar(M)=coéq F(A')->F(A).

$ 3.1: Cocomplete tensor categories

Déf 3.1: tensor category=symmetric monoidal category, tensor functor=strong
monoidal functor. Cocomplete tensor category: cocomplete + A⊗− is
cocontinuous.
En particulier, si C cocomplète tensor,
⊕(A⊗B_i) → A⊗⊕B_i est un iso, ie C est un anneau sans unité catégorifié.
Note: si C est closed, alors ⊗ est left-adjoint du Hom interne, donc C est
cocomplète.

Exemple 3.1.6: quantales = cocomplete tensor preorder.
• The unit interval [0, 1] with the usual monoid and order structure.
• The quantale of ideals of a commutative ring R with the ideal product and the inclusion relation.
• The quantale of open subsets of a topological space with the intersection and the inclusion relation.
The internal Hom is the Heyting implication and written ( a −→ b ).

Remark 3.1.14.
If R is a commutative ring, then the module category Mod(R) is a 2-initial object of Cat_c⊗/R [cocomplete R-linear tensor categories]. In fact, for every C ∈ Cat_c⊗/R the external tensor product Mod(R)→C, M→M⊗_R O_C is a cocontinuous tensor functor which is essentially unique.
Déf 3.1.15: Cat_c⊗/Mod(R) = Cat_c⊗/R (cocomplete tensor categories under
Mod(R)=cocomplete R-linear tensor categories by the above)

Remark 3.1.17: any  locally  presentable  tensor  category  is closed.
This is because the functors A⊗− : C→C are cocontinuous, hence have a right adjoint.

Lemma 3.1.20: (Tensor product of presentations)
- le produit tensoriel de 2 épis est un épi
- on a la présentation suivante du produit tensoriel de deux présentations
  A_i => B_i -> P_i:
  (A_1 ⊗ B_2)⊕(B_1 ⊗ A_2) ⇒ B_1 ⊗ B_2 → P_1 ⊗ P_2 .
In particular, the tensor product of two regular epimorphisms is again a regular epimorphism.

Proposition 3.1.21 (Tensorial  extension):
If C is an R-linear abelian tensor category, D is any finitely cocomplete R-linear tensor category and C′ is a full replete tensor subcategory of C with the properties as in Proposition 2.5.1, then there is an equivalence of categories between R-linear tensor functors C′ → D satisfying the right exactness property and right exact R-linear tensor functors C→D.

$ Section 3.2: categorification, Section 3.3: element notation.

$ 3.4: Adjunction between stacks and cocomplete tensor categories

Proposition 3.4.3 (Adjunction between Spec and Qcoh).
If F is a stack and C is a cocomplete tensor category, then there is a natural equivalence Hom_Stack(F,Spec(C)) = Hom_c⊗(C,Qcoh(F))
- a stack is  a  pseudo-functor Sch^op → Cat which  satisfies  effective descent with respect to the fpqc topology (on demande pas une fibration en groupoides)
- Spec(C)(X) = Hom_c⊗(C,Qcoh(X))
- Qcoh(F) is defined as Hom_Stack(F, Qcoh(−)), ie a quasi-coherent module M on F is given by functors M_X : F(X) → Qcoh(X) for  every  scheme X, which are compatible with base change.

Remark 3.4.9 (Artin’s criteria) Criteria for Spec(C) to be an algebraic
stack.

$ 4.1: Algebra and modules
Déf: algebra = monoid in the tensor category C.
Tensor algebra: Si C cocomplète, Alg(C)->C a pour adjoint à gauche T(M)=\sum M^n.
The tensor product of commutative algebra is the coproduct in CAlg(C);
CAlg(C) is cocomplete when C is.

Déf 4.1.6: si C est closed, le centre de A est l'équalisateur de
A->Hom(A,A) via la multiplication à gauche et à droite.

Def 4.1.7: si C closed, se donner un module à droite r:M⊗A -> M c'est
la même que se donner le dual de r:M->Hom(A,M). Se donner un module à
gauche A⊗M -> M c'est pareil que de se donner A->Hom(M,M). Mod(A)=modules à
droite.

Example 4.1.8 (Free modules).
The forgetful functor Mod(A)→C has a left adjoint which maps X∈C to the right A -module (X⊗A,X⊗m), the free A-module on X.

Définition 4.1.9: M (A,B)-bimodule [ie A⊗M⊗B → M], N (B,C)-bimodule, alors 
M ⊗_B N est le (A,C)-bimodule donné par le coéq: M ⊗ B ⊗ N ⇒ M ⊗ N -> M ⊗_B N.
la structure de (A,C)-bimodule est donnée par
A ⊗ M ⊗ N ⊗ C → M ⊗ N → M ⊗_B N
qui descend en A ⊗ ( M ⊗_B N) ⊗ C → M ⊗_B N

Proposition 4.1.10 (The tensor category of modules) .
Let C be a cocomplete tensor category and A be a commutative algebra in C,
then Mod(A) becomes a cocomplete tensor category with unit A and tensor
product ⊗_A. Colimits are created by the forgetful functor Mod(A)→C:
On a une structure de A-module sur une colimite via (colim Mi)⊗A=colim(Mi⊗A)→colim Mi.
Moreover, its left adjoint −⊗ A : C → Mod(A) becomes a cocontinuous tensor
functor, on vérifie que ⊗_A commute avec les colimites car c'est le cas de ⊗; etil est tensoriel car (S⊗A)⊗_A(T⊗A)=(S⊗T)⊗A.

Remark 4.1.11 (Restriction and extension of scalars).
Given a homomorphism of algebras A → B we obtain a forgetful functor Mod(B) → Mod(A), M→ M|A (restriction of scalars). It is left adjoint to Mod(A) → Mod(B), N → N ⊗_A B (extension of scalars).

Proposition 4.1.13 (Rank is unique).
Let C be a cocomplete R-linear tensor category. Let A be a commutative algebra in C with A \ne 0 such that A⊕n = A⊕m as A-modules for some n,m ∈ N. Then n = m. If C is locally finitely presentable, the same holds for all cardinals n,m.

Proof. By considering Mod(A) instead of C we may assume that A = O, the unit of C. We know that S:=End(O) is a commutative R-algebra such that S \ne 0. Applying Hom(O,−): C → Mod(S) to the given isomorphism O⊕n=O⊕m, we obtain an isomorphism of S-modules S⊕n=S⊕m. It is known that this implies n = m.

Proposition 4.1.15 (Lagrange’s Theorem).
Let C be a tensor category. Let A → B be a homomorphism of algebras in C . Let M be a free right B -module. Assume that B | A is a free right A -module. Then the right A -module M | A is also free. Specifically, if M = T ⊗ B in Mod(B) and B|A = S⊗A in Mod(A), then M|A =(T⊗S)⊗A.

Proof. We have M|A = (T⊗B)|A = T⊗ B|A = T⊗(S⊗A) = (T⊗ S)⊗A.

Definition 4.1.17 (A-algebras).
If C is a cocomplete tensor category and A is a commutative algebra in C, then an A-algebra is an algebra in the cocomplete tensor category Mod(A). Equivalently, an A-algebra is an algebra B in C equipped with a morphism A → Z(B) of algebras (if the center exists), i.e. a morphism of algebras f : A → B with the property that mB◦(f⊗B)= mB◦S_B,B◦(f⊗B). Thus, a commutative A-algebra is equivalently a commutative algebra B in C equipped with a homomorphism A → B.

Remark 4.1.18 (Homomorphism modules).
With the notations above, if C is closed and has equalizers, then Mod(A) is also closed and has equalizers. Specifically, for A-modules M,N we have that their internal hom Hom A(M,N) is the equalizer of the morphism Hom(M,N) → Hom(M, Hom(A,N)) which is induced by the (dualized) action of A on N and the morphism Hom(M,N) → Hom(M ⊗ A,N)=Hom(M, Hom(A,N)) which  is  induced  by  the  action  of A on M. 

Définition 4.1.19: Hopf algebra.
Bialgebras = coalgebras in the tensor category of algebras in C, ie A→A⊗A.
Hopf  algebras = bialgebras A equipped with a morphism (inversion) S:A→A.

Example 4.1.20.
Hopf algebras in Mod(R) are Hopf algebras over R in the usual sense, whereas Hopf algebras in Set are just groups. Therefore, from the tensor categorical point of view these two concepts are really the same. An easy but useful observation is that Hopf algebras are preserved by tensor functors. If we apply this to the unique cocontinuous tensor functor Set→C and some group G (in Set), we obtain a Hopf algebra O_C[G] in C, a generalization of the usual group algebra.

Remark 4.1.21 (Lie  algebras).

$ 4.2 Ideals and affine scheme
C locally presentable balanced tensor category.

A commutative algebra in C, ideal of A = subobject of A in Mod(A).
=> ideal sum ⊕Ii ->> ∑Ii ↪ A; ideal product I⊗J ->> I·J ↪ A.

Lemma 4.2.5: ideal product is commutative and associative, distributive
over arbitrary sum, A is the neutral element => ideals(A) is a quantale.

Prime ideal: I.J \subset P => I \subset P ou J \subset P.
Prop 4.2.7: if A \ne 0 is finitely presentable, it has a maximal proper
ideal which is prime.

Definition 4.2.8 (Zariski topology). Standard def.

For the structure sheaf, we have that
if X is a noetherian scheme, then we have Deligne’s formula [GD71, Proposition 6.9.17]: If M is a quasi-coherent module on X and U ⊆ X is an open subset, then the canonical homomorphism colim_{V(I)∩U=∅} Hom_OX(I,M) → Γ(U,M) is an isomorphism. Here, I runs over all quasi-coherent ideals of O X such that V(I)∩U=∅, or equivalently I|U=O_U.
=> on utilise la même définition sur C pour définir le faisceau associé à M
\in Mod(A). En particulier O_Spec(A) est un faisceau de monoides
commutatifs (resp. d'anneaux commutatifs si C est linéaire).

Definition 4.2.10 (schemes) Category Sch / C of schemes relative to C.

Example 4.2.11.
In case of C = Ab we obtain the category of usual schemes, for C = Mod(R) the category of R-schemes, for C = Set the category of monoid schemes and for C = Set∗ the category of pointed monoid schemes.

Theorem 4.2.12 (Reconstruction).
Let X be a noetherian scheme. Then there is an isomorphism of ringed spaces X = Spec(O_X) (ici O_X est vu comme un objet de QCoh(X)).

