$ 4.5 Derivation

$ 4.6 Flat object

Flat: M⊗− : C → C is left exact.
M∈C is called faithfully flat if M ⊗− preserves and reflects finite limit.

Attention: si X est un schéma, on dit en général que M est plat ssi les
fibres M_x sont plates. Brandenburg appelle ça localement plat.

Lemma 4.6.2. Every locally flat quasi-coherent module is also flat. The converse holds over quasi-separated schemes as well as over geometric stacks.

$ 4.7 Dualisable objects
M dualisable (<=>)
- e:M∗⊗M→O_C, c:O_C→M⊗M∗ satisfaisant les bons diagrammes
- e:M∗⊗M→O_C induit Hom(A,B⊗M∗)=Hom(A⊗M,B)
- c:O_C→M⊗M∗ induit Hom(A⊗M,B)=Hom(A,B⊗M∗)
- −⊗M∗ est adjoint à gauche de −⊗M.
Rem: M is dual to M∗ if and only if M∗ is dual to M.

Remark 4.7.3 (Perfect pairings)
e : A ⊗ B → L perfect pairing s'il existe c : L→ B ⊗ A qui fait commuter
les bons diagrammes. Si L est inversible, alors L⊗^{−1}⊗A est dual de B.

Ex: Serre-duality H^k(F)⊗H^{n−k}(F^∗⊗ω◦)→H^n(ω) for a coherent sheaf F on a smooth projective  variety  of  dimension n; exterior power ∧ : Λ^k(V) ⊗ Λ^{n−k}(V)→Λ^n(V)

Lemma 4.7.4.
Let M be a dualizable object in a cocomplete tensor category C. Then M is flat. If OC is finitely presentable, then M is also finitely presentable. 

Proposition 4.7.5 (The case of schemes).
Let X be a scheme, or even algebraic stack, and M ∈ Qcoh ( X). Then the following are equivalent:
1. M is dualizable in the sense above.
2. M is locally free of finite rank.
3. M is flat and of finite presentation.
4. If U is an affine scheme which maps to X, then the pullback M|U is associated to a finitely generated projective module.

Dual morphisms: Hom(V,W) = Hom(W∗⊗V, O_C) = Hom(W∗,V∗)

Lemma 4.7.9 (Duals invert).
Let η:F→G be a morphism of tensor functors F,G:C→D. If V∈C is dualizable, then η ( V) : F ( V) → G ( V) is an isomorphism. In particular, if C is a cocomplete tensor category in which the dualizable objects are colimit-dense, then Hom_c⊗(C,D) is a groupoid.

$ 4.8 Invertible objects
Definition 4.8.1 (Invertible objects).
Let C be a tensor category. Recall that an object L∈C is called invertible if there is an object K∈C such that L⊗K = O_C.

On a une notion de cohérence sur les objets invertibles:
for every isomorphism c : O_C → L⊗L^⊗−, alors L^⊗− est le dual de L d'une
unique manière.

Example 4.8.2 (The case of schemes).
Let X be a locally ringed space and M∈Mod(X).  Then M is invertible (as defined above) if and only if M is locally free of rank 1. In this case, M^⊗−1 = Hom(M, O X).

Si L est invertible, il induit une involution sur End(O_C)
via O_C → L⊗L^⊗−1 L^⊗−1 ⊗ L → O_C

A line object in C is an invertible object with signature id, i.e.  an invertible object which is symtrivial. For  example,  if X is  a  scheme  (or  algebraic  stack),  then  we have seen above that in fact every invertible object in Qcoh(
X) is a line object.

Lemma 4.8.9. Si e:E → L est un épi, alors on a E^⊗2 ⊗ L^⊗−1 ⇒ E → L est exact
ssi e est régulier.
Intuitively, in that case, e(a)⊗e(b)=e(b)⊗e(a) is the “only relation” between the generators e of L.

$ 4.9 Locally free object

$ 4.10 Descent theory
Definition 4.10.1 (Descent data).
Let A be a commutative algebra in C. The category of descent-data Desc(A) has as objects pairs (N,φ), where N∈Mod(A) and φ:A⊗N=N⊗A is an isomorphism of A⊗A-modules, de telle sorte que le triangle commute.
A ⊗ A ⊗ N -> A ⊗ N ⊗ A
    \        /
     >      <
     N ⊗ A ⊗ N

Let F: C → Desc(A) mapping M→(M⊗A,ψ); A a descent algebra if this functor is an equivalence of categories.

Remark 4.10.2.
In general, the forgetful functor Desc(A) → Mod(A) is faithful and conservative (i.e. reflects isomorphisms). Hence, if A is a descent algebra, then C → Mod(A), M → M⊗ A is faithful and conservative.

Proposition 4.10.4 (Adjunction).
Assume that C has equalizers. Let A be a commutative algebra in C with unit u : O → A. Then the canonical functor F : C → Desc(A) has a right adjoint G which maps (N,φ) to the equalizer of the two morphisms N → A ⊗ N → N ⊗ A, l'un venant de φ, l'autre de u.

Proposition 4.10.5 (Faithfully flat descent).
Assume that C has equalizers. Let A be a commutative algebra in C such that 
1. A is a flat object of C.
2. For every M∈C the canonical sequence M → M ⊗ A ⇒ M ⊗ A ⊗ A is exact.
Then A is a descent algebra.
In particular, every faithfully flat commutative algebra is a descent algebra

Definition  4.10.6 (Special  descent  algebras)
=> these are descent algebra that are stable under any cocontinuous linear
tensor.

Par exemple, si π : P → X such that π and P are  affine est une
présentation d'un stack d'Adams, Then A = π_∗ O_P is  a special descent algebra in Qcoh(X).

$ 4.11 Cohomology
Definition 4.11.1 (Cohomology).
Let C be a cocomplete R-linear tensor category with unit O_C. Then we have the global section functor Γ:C→Mod(R), A→Γ(A):=Hom(O_C,A). It is left exact.

$ 5.1.1 Free tensor categorie
We have a left adjoint of the forgetful 2-functor from (resp. symmetric) monoidal categories (with strong (resp. symmetric) monoidal functors) to categories.
On a aussi un adjoint à gauche du foncteur d'oubli symmetric monoidal
category -> monoidal category.

